Let's start off with the basic one. When did you get interested or when did
you're interested in art development? I think it developed when I was born. My

00:51.760 --> 01:01.220
father's always worked as a... worked in the space industry or in the missiles
and space industry, So I had that input around me. He had always been reading

01:01.220 --> 01:12.080
science fiction since I was young, so I had the magazines around to look at. And
some of my earliest recollections are of looking at the covers of old amazing

01:12.080 --> 01:20.420
stories, magazines or paperback books. And in fact, some of them influenced me
to a great deal. Before I could even read or write, I remember looking at some

01:20.420 --> 01:36.020
of those covers for hours and absorbing the visual feeling of the paintings.
There were a few that were especially captivating for me. And I remember them to

01:36.020 --> 01:44.460
this day, exactly what the paintings looked like. And I can describe to you the
compositions and some of the colors of the paintings. And it's a funny thing. At

01:44.460 --> 01:53.080
the last World Science Fiction Convention, I was walking down by one of the
dealer's tables in the dealer's room. and I just started going through some of

01:53.080 --> 02:01.980
the paperback books and I saw one of the covers that I remembered from when I
was three years old or whatever. It was interesting to me because I hadn't been

02:01.980 --> 02:11.060
able, in retrospect, to pinpoint the exact time when I started really being
fascinated by science fiction imagery. And this book had been published in 1952

02:11.060 --> 02:21.800
or 1953, so being born in 1950 that pretty much establishes the beginning of
that at around three years old or so. but the fact that it meant so much to me

02:21.800 --> 02:32.200
that I remembered that exact cover until my present age says something about how
I guess it was just a part of me that that kind of imagery was important to me.

02:32.760 --> 02:43.240
But later when I began to read, I became an avid reader of all types of
literature, but especially science fiction and fantasy. And I had an interest in

02:43.240 --> 02:52.460
art, so the two combined, and it seemed natural to me too. to read and try to
draw what I read. And I would come home sometimes from science-fiction movies or

02:52.460 --> 03:01.140
movies that I enjoyed and tried to illustrate scenes that I'd seen in the movie
from memory. And that carried on pretty much right into my college years.

03:04.940 --> 03:21.580
I can continue beyond that point. Because in college, I had been laboring under
the assumption that I had to have a real type of profession. This is largely due

03:21.580 --> 03:29.500
to input from my parents, but I felt that I had to be something professional,
like a lawyer, something respectable, which being an artist isn't.

03:32.340 --> 03:40.800
So I was diverted during my college years into wanting to become a doctor, which
is still a major interest of mine, anatomy and physiology and the sciences in

03:40.800 --> 03:51.080
general were always important to me. But about three quarters of the way through
my college education, I decided to abandon my pre-med training and go full

03:51.080 --> 03:59.180
scale. Well, actually, it wasn't until my last year of college that I decided a
full tilt to go into illustrating or painting, and I graduated with a degree in

03:59.180 --> 04:08.560
painting. If I had taken one more course, I would have had a degree in biology
with an emphasis on anatomy and physiology, human anatomy and physiology. To go

04:08.560 --> 04:16.480
up and attack on that, does that background, or how does that background help
you when you're painting? It helps me a lot in several ways. First of all, in

04:16.480 --> 04:31.100
constructing alien forms by just extrapolating upon comparative biology. I can
develop a life form that's both interesting visually and somewhat convincingly

04:31.100 --> 04:41.320
suited for a particular environment on another planet. There's that. And also,
it helps me in constructing a human form because I did a lot of dissection. and

04:41.320 --> 04:51.300
I know my human anatomy fairly well. Whereas I know a lot of artists who don't,
they know surface anatomy but they can't really construct a person well out of

04:51.300 --> 05:00.260
their imagination without at least the extensive use of photographs and that's
something I try to avoid. I think it shows in an artist's painting when one uses

05:00.260 --> 05:07.100
a photograph to develop the person and then tries to create the rest of the
painting out of one's imagination, you see a real dichotomy between the way the

05:07.100 --> 05:17.400
person's painted and the rest of the painting is painted. If it all comes out of
your mind, then it all looks like one product or whatever. But one of the jobs I

05:17.400 --> 05:26.500
had when I was putting myself through college was working in the anatomy and
physiology labs at the university I went to preparing the cadavers for the

05:26.500 --> 05:35.380
classes. And during that time, I managed to get some work in doing medical
illustrations. All this combined to really give me a good fundamental education

05:35.380 --> 05:47.620
in the way the body is made up. You had some further training going in, are you?
Yes, after college I went to, I wasn't, the teachers told me I was ready for a

05:47.620 --> 05:53.800
professional career, but I didn't know what I wanted to do yet. I mean, I still
didn't, well, I knew what I wanted to do, but I didn't have the confidence

05:53.800 --> 06:02.460
really to throw everything I had into a career in illustration. I didn't know
