14:39.880 --> 14:48.060
airbrush work right up to the foreground and make a painting that's completely
airbrush My cover for Arthur C. Clarke's book, 2010, approaches that. There is a

14:48.060 --> 14:55.200
lot of airbrush work in the foreground there. But that was such a simple
composition that it pretty much required that, I think.

14:59.000 --> 15:10.680
What about using oils and acrylics? I know you prefer acrylics. Well, I prefer
acrylics for illustration because they dry so quickly. That's the only reason,

15:10.780 --> 15:19.400
really. Well, there's two reasons, actually, why I like to use acrylics. They
dry so quickly, and it's the main reason, and that's the reason why I first

15:19.400 --> 15:28.700
started using them. My training had all been in oils and watercolors, and a lot
of my early illustrations were in those two media, but I found myself often

15:28.700 --> 15:37.140
working at 3 o'clock in the morning before the day, or the morning of the day
that I had to turn a painting in, and I couldn't bring a painting in wet, so I'd

15:37.140 --> 15:45.080
have to make so much drier in with the painting. and there's a substance called
cobalt dryer that if you put too much in the paint, it seriously affects the

15:45.080 --> 15:55.600
longevity of the painting. In fact, I have a painting I did in late 1974 that
has now cracked up a lot in oil painting because I had to rush it dry that way.

15:56.680 --> 16:04.280
And so my feeling is if I can't paint an oil painting right so that it will last
and be a good investment to someone who may buy it, then I'd rather not use that

16:04.280 --> 16:16.640
medium at all unless I have the time to be able to develop it in the correct
process so that it'll last for posterity. So I use acrylics and it certainly is

16:16.640 --> 16:24.780
easier for me. I can paint right up to two minutes before the messenger comes to
pick up my painting and take it to the publisher and put in that last little

16:24.780 --> 16:34.900
highlight or whatever and not have to worry about it being wet or being damaged
on root. Some people say acrylics don't have the depth that oils have, but I had

16:34.900 --> 16:41.340
to notice the acrylic paints. Oh, it depends on how you use them. Yeah, I see a
lot of flat acrylic paintings, frankly.

16:44.220 --> 16:53.380
And that's just, I had to teach myself how to use them. And I think my
background in oils dictated that I try to duplicate some of the feeling that you

16:53.380 --> 17:03.400
get in oil paintings with acrylics. And maybe because I approach it from that
aspect, I attempted to do that, to get that feeling in depth with my acrylic set

17:03.400 --> 17:12.020
and other people who have just had a training in acrylics only don't try to do
that because they feel limited by that. The fast drying time is also a liability

17:12.020 --> 17:20.960
with acrylics. It's very hard to blend large areas of color, and that's why I
often resort to the airbrush. I can do it with watches if I have to, but it

17:20.960 --> 17:31.820
takes a lot longer. I did a painting for a book by Clifford Simak called City.
There's a big blue sky in the background, and it took me 32 washes of color to

17:31.820 --> 17:39.980
get just the right gradations of blues in the background. That took me about a
day and a half or two days to do. Now, with an airbrush, I probably could have

17:39.980 --> 17:49.980
gotten exactly the same effect in a half an hour. So, you know, when you're
working a 100-hour week or an 80-hour week like I do, you know, a half an hour

17:49.980 --> 17:57.820
can make a big difference in a painting. So I don't... I'm like... Wait a
minute, let me say... I don't work 80 or 100-hour weeks all the time, but I

17:57.820 --> 18:08.360
often do. It seems like most of the last year I did. That half an hour or two
days worth of time makes a big difference. I resort to the airbrush just because

18:08.360 --> 18:11.060
it is a good time-saving tool, and I can duplicate the same effects.

18:15.380 --> 18:27.220
I like oil paints a lot, and I want to get back into using them just because it
has a whole historical, romantic feeling to it. It's really something that's

18:27.220 --> 18:36.400
